{
  "doc_id": "14006",
  "text": "Strikingly, a number of genes involved in antigen presentation are down-regulated and fall within cluster e. This functional group includes the MHC class I h-2d gene and MHC-related molecules cd1d1, mr1, h2-t10 and h2-t3. The latter two genes encode thymus leukemia (TL) antigens which bind CD8a homodimers [CITATION_1] . The non-classical MHC class I molecule MR1 has recently been shown to be involved in the selection of mucosal-associated invariant T cells [CITATION_2] . Also part of this group are ctse and ctsl, the cathepsins E and L genes, which are involved in antigen processing [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . CD1d1 and cathepsin L are important for the development of NKT cells [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Finally, the ifngr gene is also down-regulated. Signaling by the IFN-g receptor induces many genes within the MHC locus and its down-regulation may thus enhance the decrease in MHC class I molecules noted above (41).",
